JHA's sack total is nothing to write home about, but he is eighth in the league with 23 pressures. For context, that is more than T.J. Watt (22), Danielle Hunter (20), and Tuli Tuipulotu (21). Tap JHA as a top-25 option for Week 12, thanks to a plus matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Simmons showed up in Week 11, reeling off two solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The Titans' defensive tackle is up to 5.5 sacks on the season and can be counted as a DT1/DL2 option where needed for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Jaelan showed up in Week 11, racking up two solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Phillips has been making an impact since joining the Eagles and has now recorded his first sack with his new team. Tap Jalean as a DL3 option for a neutral-at-best on-paper matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Quinnen was excellent in Week 11, racking up one solo, three assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Yes, the opponent was the Las Vegas Raiders, but the Cowboys' interior defensive line was looking downright dominant on Monday night. The sack was the first since back in Week 1 for Williams, who remains in the DL3 mix mainly because of name equity and talent, not production. Tap Quineen as a low-floor DL3 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Dallas Turner showed up in Week 11, reeling off two solos, five assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. The talented edge rusher was able to take advantage of Jonathan Greenard's absence to record his first full sack since Week 2. Now up to 2.5 on the season, Turner should get at least one more start with Greenard missing both Thursday and Friday practices last week. Tap Dallas as a DL3 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Myles Murphy showed up in Week 11, reeling off four solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Murphy is making the most of the extra burn he is getting with both Trey Hendrickson and Shermar Stewart sidelined, tallying his first sack since Week 5. Myles is up to a solid 2.5 sacks on the season and can be treated as a DL3 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Armstead was excellent in Week 11, racking up two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Now up to an impressive 5.5 sacks on the season, Arik has notched a sack in each of his last two games. Tap Armstead as a top-25 DL option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals. Make the add wherever available.

Arden Key showed up in Week 11, tallying two solos, one assist, 1.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. Now up to three sacks on the season, Key has recorded at least a half sack in each of his last three games. Those contests were spread out due to Arden dealing with a quad injury, as this was the veteran pass rusher's first game since back in Week 5. Tap Key as a DL3 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

LaCale showed up in Week 11, notching three solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. London has recorded all three of his sacks in his last two games and has a nice two game stretch coming up against New Orleans and the New York Jets for fantasy managers to take advantage of. He has yet to top 50 percent of the snaps this season, so he remains more of a deep league target than someone to plug into lineups in 12-team leagues. Start LaCale in 16+ team leagues where needed.

DaQuan Jones showed up in Week 11, racking up two solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. The Sack was just the third of the season for the Bills' defensive tackle, but he remains off the radar for those in DL leagues. Tap him as a low-end DT2 where needed, but look elsewhere for your Week 12 DL3.

Campbell was at it again in Week 11, reeling off seven solos, eight assists, and one tackle for loss. The Lions linebacker has transformed into an elite IDP contributor this season and should be counted as a top-five option regardless of opponent. Treat him as such for a plus Week 12 matchup against the New York Giants.

Gray was at it again in Week 11, stacking six solos, five assists, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. The Titans linebacker has provided LB1-level production since Week 4, and needs to be counted as a top-10 option. Treat Gray as a top-10 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Landman was excellent in Week 11, tallying six solos, one assist, and one forced fumble. Landman is the LB4 in fppg heading into Week 12 and should be treated as a top-10 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Cashman was excellent in Week 11, racking up six solos and nine assists. Cashman has been producing at an LB1 level since he returned from injury and should be treated as a top-15 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Carson was excellent in Week 11, reeling off eight solos, three assists, two tackles for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. The rookie linebacker has provided LB1 production over the last two weeks, putting him in the top-25 conversation for Week 12. Treat him as such for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Spillane showed up in Week 11, tallying five solos, four assists, and one pass defended. Spillane has had a peaks-and-valleys type of season, but is the LB18 in fppg due to some massive spike weeks. Tap Spillane as a top-20 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Kaden Elliss was excellent in Week 11, racking up five solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Elliss has been a steady LB2 force this season and should continue to be treated as one for a plus Week 12 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Bernard showed up in Week 11, tallying eight solos, three assists, two tackles for loss, and two passes defended. The Bills' middle linebacker has recorded four or more solos in six of his last seven games, but has failed to make good on his LB1 upside this season, producing more in line with a low-end LB2. Tap Bernard as a top-25 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Dee Winters showed up in Week 11, tallying five solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Winters has bounced between LB2 and LB3 value this season due to inconsistency. The 49ers linebacker has slowed considerably since his hot start over the first four weeks of the season. Tap Dee as a top-25 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Quincy Williams was at it again in Week 11, ripping off six solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. All it took was the Jets to demote him for Quincy to step it up and put together two LB1-level outings. Treat the motivated linebacker as a top-15 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Zaire was excellent in Week 10, tallying six solos, four assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Franklin turned in his best fantasy output in a down season in Week 10, as he has managed four or more solos just four times all season. Despite the name equity, fantasy managers should count him as more of an LB2 than LB1 until he proves his Week 10 outburst was not a fluke. Fire Zaire up as a top-24 play for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Queen showed up in Week 11, racking up five solos and five assists. Queen has been an LB4 since the Steelers bye, and his production this past weekend does nothing to change that. He is capable of spike weeks but has been a waiver wire level producer for most of the season. Stash him where needed, but keep him far from lineups despite the strong Week 11 production and the plus matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Simon showed up in Week 11, reeling off four solos and eight assists on 100 percent of the snaps. Simon has stepped in as a starter since Mack Wilson has been sidelined, and looks like he can provide solid LB3/4 production in the interim. Tap the rookie linebacker as an LB3 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Devin Bush showed up in Week 11, racking up two solos, two assists, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. Bush has struggled in the solo tackle department over the last four weeks, dropping him to LB3 status for the foreseeable future. Even this spike week was a forgettable day outside of the pick six. Still, he has more than enough upside to keep tapping as an LB3/4 option.

Cody Barton showed up in Week 11, racking up two solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and three passes defended. Barton has fallen off a cliff in the solo department, failing to top two solos since all the way back in Week 5, but has still managed to secure back-to-back spike weeks thanks to a pick six and a sack. Treat the Titans' everydown linebacker as an LB3 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Robinson showed up in Week 11, reeling off five solos and seven assists. Robinson played 68 percent of the snaps against Arizona due to Tatum Bethune leaving the game with a high ankle sprain, an injury that suggests that Robinson will see an increased role in Week 12 as well. Tap the veteran lienbacker as an LB3 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Isaiah McDuffie got some extra burn in Week 11, finishing the afternoon with five solos, six assists, and 0.5 sacks. McDuffie has been a strong spot starter in the past and may be called upon again for Week 12 if Quay Walker (shoulder) is sidelined. Fire McDuffie up as a borderline LB2 option if he indeed gets the start against the Minnesota Vikings.

Micah was excellent in Week 11, reeling off one solo, five assists, 1.5 sacks, and one forced fumble. Parsons has been a little more inconsistent than IDP managers may have hoped, but such is the life of edge rushers. Now up to a strong eight sacks on the season, Micah will look to take advantage of multiple plus matchups through the stretch run.

AVG showed up in Week 11, racking up two solos, six assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. The sack was the first for Van Ginkel since back in Week 3, as the veteran edge rusher has missed multiple games due to injury this season. Still, AVG should be viewed as more of a low-end DL3 than the DL2 fantasy managers were likely hoping for when they added him to rosters. Treat him as such for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Kyle Hamilton has been excellent in Week 11, reeling off six solos, three assists, one sack, three tackles for loss, one forced fumble, and two passes defended. The outing was a breath of fresh air for the talented safety, who has had more down weeks than strong weeks this season. Continue to treat Hamilton as a low-floor DB1 for a plus Week 12 matchup against the New York Jets.

Kam Curl was excellent in Week 11, tallying nine solos and two assists. Curl had been a little quiet since the team's Week 8 bye, so his Week 11 performance is a welcome sign from the talented safety. Tap Curl as a top-12 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Moehrig was at it again in Week 11, reeling off six solos and five assists. Tre'von has become an IDP force as a member of the Panthers, checking in as the DB5 in fppg on the season. Tap the talented safety as a DB1 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Jessie Bates showed up in Week 11, tallying six solos and two assists. Bates dropped out of the DB1 mix this season, and even two consecutive excellent weeks can't put him back in that conversation. Tap Bates as a DB2 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Chamarri was excellent in Week 11, racking up five solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The DB19 in fppg on the season, Chamarri has been more inconsistent than fantasy managers may have hoped, but has made up for it with his spike weeks. Tap Conner as a top-25 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Bishop was at it again in Week 11, reeling off three solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Cole has snagged a pick in back-to-back games and is creeping closer and closer to top-15 status. For now, continue to treat him as a top-25 option.

Nick Cross was excellent in Week 10, racking up three solos, four assists, and one sack. Cross checks into Week 11 as the DB11 in fppg and the DB3 overall, and should be treated as such for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Kevin Byard showed up in Week 11, racking up two solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Byrard has been a solid DB2 option since the bye week, but it looks like he will not creep back into the top-10 conversation again this season. Tap the veteran safety as a top-25 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Cooper Dejean showed up in Week 11, racking up three solos, one interception, and two passes defended. DeJean has become a fantasy force this season, cementing himself as a top-25 option regardless of opponent. Tap Cooper as a DB2 play for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Dugger showed up in Week 11, racking up three solos, one interception, two passes defended, and one touchdown. Dugger has been playing an everydown role for the Steelers, but has yet to flash his DB1 skills outside of the pick six. For now, treat him as a DB2/3 de[emdomg on the matchup. Tap him as a DB2 option for Week 12, thanks to a plus matchup against the Chicago Bears. Make the add in all competitive leagues.

Hooker was excellent in Week 11, reeling off eight solos, one assist, and one pass defended. Amani is in the midst of his most productive three game stretch of the season and has recorded six or more solos in each of his last two. Count Hooker as an upside DB3 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

DaRon Bland was excellent in Week 11, reeling off six solos, four assists, and two passes defended. DaRon has been on fire since Week 7, checking in as the DB3 in fppg in that time span. Tap Bland as a top-15 option as long as he is cooking, including this week, despite a neutral-at-best matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Harrison was at it again in Week 11, tallying nine solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Ronnie is starting to heat up for Atlanta, registering five or more solos in each of his last two games. It took him a couple of games, but the veteran safety is starting to make an impact for the Falcons since being signed to the active roster in Week 8. Tap Harrison as a borderline DB2 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Alontae had his best fantasy game of the season in Week 10, tallying four solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Taylor has now recorded four or more solos in four of his last five, working his way into the DB2 mix, despite no byes this week. Tap Alonate as a top-25 option for a plus matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Kamren Kinchens showed up in Week 11, tallying three solos, one assist, two interceptions, and two passes defended against Sam Darnold and the Seattle Seahawks. Kinchens started the season strong, but has had just two plus outings since Week 3, making him more of a DB3 than a DB2 for Week 12. Treat him as such for a plus Week 12 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Evan Williams showed up in Week 11, reeling off five solos, four assists, one interception, and one pass defended in what was the talented corner's best fantasy game of the season. Williams has put together two straight plus outings despite being a low-floor DB3 option, so perhaps this is a sign of good things to come. Tap Williams as a top-36 option for a plus Week 12 matchup against J.J. McCarthy and the Minnesota Vikings. Start Williams where needed.

Bynum showed up in Week 10, reeling off four solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble.
